{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.82,0.02,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108758"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2596"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91128"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1049"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108758"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea. Three days ago, she commenced her first course of chemotherapy for non-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma. She has a medical history of cytomegalovirus infection at age 14. Her only regular medication is the chemotherapy regimen. She had two day old takeaway food yesterday.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Physical examination is otherwise unremarkable. An ECG reveals prolonged PR intervals and broadened QRS complexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 140 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 6.1 mmol/L (3.5-5.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 100 mmol/L (95-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrate 0.87 mmol/L (0.15-0.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 1.8 mmol/L (2.2-2.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate 1.79 mmol/L (0.75-1.50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase 911 U/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chemotherapy-related side effects","Tumour lysis syndrome","Cytomegalovirus colitis","Febrile neutropenia","Bacterial gastroenteritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic biochemical features of \u003Cstrong\u003Etumour lysis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E: hyperkalaemia (6.1 mmol/L), hyperphosphataemia (1.79 mmol/L), hypocalcaemia (1.8 mmol/L), hyperuricaemia (0.87 mmol/L), and elevated lactate dehydrogenase (911 U/L). The timing of symptoms, occurring shortly after starting chemotherapy for a haematological malignancy, is typical. The ECG changes of prolonged PR interval and broad QRS are consistent with hyperkalaemia, which requires urgent treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy-related side effects\u003C/strong\u003E such as nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea are common but would not explain the characteristic biochemical derangements or ECG changes seen here. In fact, chemotherapy-induced gastrointestinal symptoms typically lead to hypokalaemia rather than hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytomegalovirus colitis\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in immunocompromised patients but typically presents with more severe abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea. The biochemical abnormalities would not be consistent with CMV colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFebrile neutropenia\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in any patient receiving chemotherapy who develops fever. However, the characteristic biochemical abnormalities point to a different diagnosis, and neutropenic sepsis would typically present with more severe systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial gastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the gastrointestinal symptoms but would not cause such marked biochemical derangements. While the history of eating old takeaway food might suggest food poisoning, the biochemical profile is diagnostic of tumour lysis syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tumour lysis syndrome presents with characteristic biochemical abnormalities: hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia, and hyperuricaemia","ECG changes of hyperkalaemia are an important early warning sign in tumour lysis syndrome","Tumour lysis syndrome typically occurs within days of starting chemotherapy for haematological malignancies"],"references":["Durani U, Hogan WJ. Emergencies in haematology: tumour lysis syndrome. British Journal of Haematology. 2020 Feb;188(4):494-500. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31774551/","Adeyinka A, Kaur A, Bashir K. Tumor Lysis Syndrome. [Updated 2024 Oct 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518985/","Barbar T, Jaffer Sathick I. Tumor Lysis Syndrome. Adv Chronic Kidney Dis. 2021 Sep;28(5):438-446.e1. doi: 10.1053/j.ackd.2021.09.007. PMID: 35190110. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35190110/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91128"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91128"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T12:10:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T12:10:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2596"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108758"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"create